ark. Md. 6th and K Sts. N.W.\nShepherd 3000 National 3000\nHill Tibbitts Triangle Motor Co.\n301 14th St. N.W. N. Y. Ave. at N. Cap St.\nNational 9350 National 3932\nWashington Motor Co.\n631 Massachusetts Ave. N.W.\nNational 9000\nA-3\nunanimously adopted by the association\nand ordered sent to George H, O'Con\nnor and Matt Horne for their enter\ntainment presented at the annual ban\nquet of the association at the Raleigh\nHotel.\nThe regular annual meeting was pre\nsided over by Theodore W. Noyes as\npresident.\nFollowing the meeting the members\nformed in a body and marched to the\nWhite House, where they joined pa\ntriotic societies In paying their respects\nto President Hoover. The group going\nto the White House was headed by\nHenry L. Bryan and other vice presi\ndents of the organisation.\nECONOMIST SEES\nPROSPERITY IN 1930\nProhibition, Science in Industry\nnnd Mass Production Please\nProf. Fisher.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDES MOINES, lowa, January I.\nProsperity for 1930, despite the linger\ning memories of the stock market erash,\nis forecast by Prof. Irving Fisher of\nYale.\nProhibition, the application of sci\nence and invention to industry and\nscientinc management in mass produc\ntion were cited as contributing factors\nfor a better business outlook. He spoke\nlast night before lowa bankers.\n\"Prohibition is a highly controversial\nsubject,\u201d Prof. Fisher said, \"but not on\nthe economic side. Whatever else we\nmay think of prohibition, there is no\ngainsaying its economic value.\n\"Future earnings may also be ex\npected to be greater, because we are\nnow applying science and invention to\nindustry as we never applied them be\nfore. Inventing is now a profession.\n\"Scientific management and mass\nproduction are contributing to in\ncreased output, which is reflected in\nincreased dividend earnings. Labor\nunions are Increasingly sympathetic\nwith scientific management and have\nlargely renounced the policy of limita\ntion of output.\u201d\nThe stock panic was laid to \"unsound\nfinancing of sound prospects.\u201d \"The\nreal trouble,\u201d he said, \"was not so much\nthe high prices of securities as thajt\nthere were too many people in debt,\nand too deeply In debt. The outlook\nwas so very bright as to dazzle the pub\nlic and lure them into debt to get rich\nquick.\u201d\nLoss of $30,000,000,000 in paper val\nues of securities was seen as no reason\nfor slowing down of business and in\ndustry.","height":"25338","width":"19848"}}
